(105, 'NIT fee raised to Rs. 1,25,000 annually from Rs. 70,000', '<p>After the academic fee hike at Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs), annual tuition fee at National Institutes of Technology NITs) has also been raised to Rs. 1,25,000 from the existing Rs. 70,000. In an official announcement, Prof. Sanjeev K Sharma, Director (NITs) shared, &ldquo;The Council after detailed deliberation unanimously decided to enhance the tuition fee being charged by the NITs from existing Rs. 70,000 to Rs. 1,25,000 per student per annum from the ensuing academic year.&rdquo;<br /><br />According to NIT Council officials, the revised academic fee will be applicable from the current academic session 2016-17. However, the existing students or the students who have taken admission across NITs prior to admission year 2016-17, would continue to pay the fee as per the existing rate. The revised annual fee would be applicable only for those candidates who would take admission in the institutes of national importance starting from 2016-17 onwards.<br /> <br />In another decision, the academic fee at Indian Institutes of Science Education and Research (IISER) has also been increased to Rs. 25,000 per semester from the existing Rs. 15,000 per semester with "prospective effect".<br /> <br />Under the new fee structure of NITs, SC/ST/PH and the most economically backward students (whose family income is less than Rs. 1 lakh per annum) will get 100 per cent fee waiver, while other economically backward students (whose family income is between Rs. 1 lakh to Rs. 5 lakh) will get remission of 2/3rd of the tuition fee.<br /> <br />Earlier, IIT Council had raised annual fee at IITs to Rs 2 Lakh from the existing Rs 90,000.<br /> <br />There are a total of 31 NITs in India, which are also the participating institutes of Joint Seat Allocation Authority (JoSAA) 2016. Admissions to these 31 institutes of national importance are offered through JoSAA counselling and seat allotment process, based on candidates&rsquo; JEE Main Ranks.<br /> </p>', 'news/img/news105.jpeg', 'img/news_b105.jpeg', 'news/php/article.php?id=105', 'fee9 hike nit9 nits national institute of99 technology 2016'),
(106, 'MHRD raises annual IIT fee by over 100 per cent', '<p>The annual academic fees for undergraduate engineering programmes at Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs) will be raised by over 100 per cent from the academic year 2016-17, said an announcement from Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD). According to a national daily that quoted the announcement made by MHRD officials, the annual fee of IIT students will be hiked from the current Rs 90,000 to Rs 2 lakh. This means that there will be an increase of over 100 per cent annual fee for B. Tech/B.E. courses at IITs.</p>\r\n<p>Though a decision in this regard has been taken, but an official notification by MHRD with details is not available yet.<br /> <br />Earlier, IIT Council had approved a proposal pertaining to annual fee hike at IITs from existing Rs 90,000 to Rs 3 Lakh, which was then submitted to MHRD for its approval. However, the decision was pending with the ministry, which has now decided to increase the academic fee from Rs 9,000 to Rs 2 lakh per annum.<br /> <br />Prior to this, the IITs had increased the annual fees in 2013 to Rs 90,000 from the earlier Rs.50,000. However, the SC, ST and economically weak students were given rebate in this. In year 2012 too, the Kakodkar committee set up by former HRD Minister Kapil Sibal had proposed various models that included zero government funding and fee hike to make IITs self-dependent for enhancing their academic quality and research capabilities. However, the recommendations were never approved due to several administrative and political reasons.</p>', 'news/img/news106.jpeg', 'img/news_b106.jpeg', 'news/php/article.php?id=106', 'fee9 hike iit9 iits indian institute of99 technology 2016 jee9'),
(107, 'Revised IIT fee applicable to new admissions from 2016-17 onwards, says MHRD', '<p>After a few days of raising the academic fees by over 100 per cent for undergraduate engineering programmes at Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs), the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) has clarified that the revised fee structure would be applicable for candidates taking admission at IITs starting from the academic year 2016-17 onwards. Thus, the candidates currently studying at IITs would continue to pay their fee as per the existing structure.</p>\r\n<p>Earlier, when the ministry had decided to increase the annual fee at IITs from Rs 90,000 to Rs 2 lakh, there was no clarification on whether the new fee structure would be applicable to the candidates who are already pursuing their B. Tech programmes at the premiere institutes.<br /> <br />However, as per a latest official notification by the MHRD, it has been made clear that the first year candidates starting their academic year from 2016-17 onwards will have to pay their fee as per the revised structure. All IIT Directors have also been asked by the ministry to take necessary actions towards the implementation of the same.<br /> <br />In 2013 also, the IITs had increased the annual fees to Rs 90,000 from the earlier Rs 50,000. However, the SC, ST and economically weak students were given rebate in this. The previous year too, in 2012, the Kakodkar committee set up by former HRD Minister Kapil Sibal had proposed various models that included zero government funding and fee hike to make IITs self-dependent for enhancing their academic quality and research capabilities. However, the recommendations were never approved due to several administrative and political reasons.</p>', 'news/img/news107.jpeg', 'img/news_b107.jpeg', 'news/php/article.php?id=107', ''),
(108, 'JoSAA extends choice filling deadline till June 29', '<p>Joint Seat Allocation Authority (JoSAA) has extended the last date for registration and choice filling till June 29 (12 pm) for candidates who are eligible to participate in JoSAA counselling and seat allotment 2016. The process of registration and choice filling for JoSAA counselling has started on June 24, and was scheduled to be closed on June 28 earlier. However, as per the latest notification of the JEE counselling authority, candidates can now fill their choices till June 29 (12 pm).</p>\r\n<p>With the extended deadline, JEE Main and JEE Advanced candidates have now got an extra day for registration and choice filling. In order to register themselves, qualified candidates have to use their JEE Main roll number and password.</p>\r\n<p>Candidates are not required to pay any fee for filling-in of choices on the online portal.<br /> <br /><a href="http://josaa.nic.in/counseling/root/Candidatelogin.aspx" target="_blank">Click here</a> for JoSAA 2016 registration and choice filling of academic programmes.<br /> <br />According to JoSAA officials, candidates are free to fill in as many choices as they want. But it&rsquo;s important for candidates to carefully prioritize the academic programmes while filling in the choices. They should take advantage of the mock seat allocation facility. If candidates do not lock their choices, the last saved choices will be locked automatically in the last minute of last date of choice filling. After locking the choices, the candidates will not be able to change their choices/preference order any more.<br /> <br />JoSAA 2016 will conduct counselling and seat allotment for JEE Main and JEE Advanced qualifying candidates, for admissions to 22 IITs and ISM Dhanbad, 31 NITs, 20 IIITs and 18 GFTIs. There will be four rounds of seat allocation and the result of first round will be announced on June 30.</p>', 'news/img/news108.png', 'img/news_b108.jpeg', 'news/php/article.php?id=108', 'josaa counselling 2016 iit9 nit9 engineering colleges ');
